<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478"><gtr:id>C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Institute of Hearing Research</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478"><gtr:id>C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Institute of Hearing Research</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/39DDCB99-3651-4B2D-9450-175D10C5DEDD"><gtr:id>39DDCB99-3651-4B2D-9450-175D10C5DEDD</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Michael</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Akeroyd</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-7182-9209</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U135079247"><gtr:id>46CF3455-A46D-41AA-B2A8-A4173E1D71B4</gtr:id><gtr:title>Binaural hearing and bilateral management</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U135079247</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Being able to tell where a sound is coming from is crucial to coping with everyday life. This &amp;quot;directional hearing&amp;quot; is best with two equal ears, but hearing impairment often affects one ear more than another, and many people are fitted with one hearing aid or have middle-ear surgery on one ear. Our goals are to further understand any auditory disabilities experienced in the domain of directional hearing, and to measure what benefits hearing aids and middle-ear surgery can offer to them.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Most hearing impairments are bilateral. It is commonly assumed that managing both impairments should confer advantages, but there is no supporting robust supporting evidence for this. In this strand of work we aim to gain insight into the advantages, by studying the applications of binaural hearing to auditory disabilities and the benefits from hearing aids. We also hope to make contributions to the psychophysical theory that underpins our applied knowledge.

The majority of the projects in this strand are concerned with measuring and understanding the dynamic properties of the binaural system. We are conducting both fundamental and applied studies of how good normal and hearing-impaired individuals are at detecting sounds that are masked by moving noises. This work is showing that some people have much worse dynamic abilities than others. We hope to extend this work to different experimental designs that reflect other aspects of how the binaural system deals with changing sounds (especially how the beginnings of sounds are processed, as they are particularly important for directional hearing).

We have completed a large-sample (about 300 people) experiment that gives us sufficient data to look for links between dynamic capacity and hearing impairment or disability. The analysis of this is continuing but we expect it to show that, even after control for hearing levels and attentional capacities, there are significant influences of the dynamics of binaural hearing on self-reports of disability in complex listening circumstances.

We are also studying the effects of middle-ear surgery. This is almost always performed on one ear - generally the poorer one - and so it either introduces an asymmetry between the ears or eliminates an asymmetry that was already present. It is therefore likely that the surgery will influence binaural hearing; accordingly, we are measuring performance on our experimental tests before and after surgery.

Note that this programme has been replaced from 2009/10 onwards by the programme &amp;quot;Auditory disability and spatial hearing&amp;quot;. See www.ihr.mrc.ac.uk/research2009/index.php?page=8 for details.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>429124</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>I developed a &amp;quot;Matlab&amp;quot; toolbox for running computational models of binaural (spatial) hearing. In recent years the software has been extended and parts have been supplied to occasional other researchers on request.</gtr:description><gtr:id>84515346-B9EF-4DF5-985A-3E41144A94C9</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The software has proved extremely useful to me and is at the heart of all our current experimental and model systems (800+ programs)</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>6E0602803C8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>2006 - Binaural toolbox for Matlab</gtr:title><gtr:type>Improvements to research infrastructure</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2006</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E2178A31-E2CF-4B93-A4BD-A7DB5E73D6B8</gtr:id><gtr:title>The binaural performance of a cross-talk cancellation system with matched or mismatched setup and playback acoustics.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/898d4c8b369e5031a93b98d7107dd1bf"><gtr:id>898d4c8b369e5031a93b98d7107dd1bf</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Akeroyd MA</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2007-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0001-4966</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>27F7182E2B8</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>842BF98F-4277-41F2-823A-BB5C1DC0D66C</gtr:id><gtr:title>The detection of differences in the cues to distance by elderly hearing-impaired listeners.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/898d4c8b369e5031a93b98d7107dd1bf"><gtr:id>898d4c8b369e5031a93b98d7107dd1bf</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Akeroyd MA</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2007-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0001-4966</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>D29069ECC5A</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>248D2C13-3669-4BA2-A80B-49EB0568206F</gtr:id><gtr:title>The psychoacoustics of binaural hearing.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>International journal of audiology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/898d4c8b369e5031a93b98d7107dd1bf"><gtr:id>898d4c8b369e5031a93b98d7107dd1bf</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Akeroyd MA</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2006-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1499-2027</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>D8CF7AB3650</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>1B9120D9-2867-4752-B755-40F6F56E20B4</gtr:id><gtr:title>Two-eared listening in dynamic situations.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>International journal of audiology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8038e3892281cf3b13d5c98f88f239